segments.text: Well, one thing you and I have talked about, one of the things that Jack Williams did better than anyone I've ever known is to write one, two, or three sentence notes to people.
And it just had the ability to make everyone feel good.
This is written
For me, it's not something that's spit out of a computer or anything like that.
It's not something that someone else had drafted for me.
And again, that's one of the things that I wish that I had and don't.
Obviously, it didn't take him a long time to write.
It may have taken a long time to think, because they were always so well stated.
It just would have been hard to improve on either.
He had good wit about him.
Physically, he made a very attractive appearance.
And he was obviously bright and very articulate.
So it just had a lot going for him.
One of the things I never understood, he was always there, there, there in Radisson to talk about his military service and his decorations and his having been wounded.
Right.
I never heard him say anything about any of that.
It was as if he didn't want anybody to think that he was trying to compete with Earl Rudder.
That's the only thing I can think of.
Well, you know, the only thing I remember
He was obviously proud to have been a Marine.
We didn't hear about his record, but he was not reticent to tell you he'd been a Marine.
As far as you can be as an objective observer, if there were any board members that disagreed or disliked, disagreed with or disliked something about Jack Williams, what were their
I think there were probably some board members who would have been more comfortable with a president with an engineering, science, technology background than one from humanities.
I think there were some who thought maybe he didn't
give agriculture and engineering as much attention as perhaps they believe they deserve.

I think that there were some board members who might have been happier if Jack Williams had been a little more prone to say what he knew they would like to hear rather than what he believed they needed to hear.
So he was not always politic in some of his statements to the board and the public about the board.
He might have been as skillful as he was.
I can't believe he didn't recognize what he was doing.
But I'm assuming that he believed a greater good call for him to do what he was doing.
Because as I think back about those two men,
I can't think of many openings, if any, that existed that each of them didn't use.
We almost got to South Texas.
But as I recall, it was only on the condition that never, never, never would any of those courses be taught anywhere else but in Houston, something like that.
And Dr. Williams, as I recall, said, no, if we're going to have a law school, I want at least part of it to be here.
Right.
And I know that, I say I know, I believe that he did want to have a law school at Texas A&M.
Let's see.
Let's go back and talk about President's wives, Mrs. Rutter and Mrs. Williams.
Well, Mrs. Rutter, you know,
amazing in that I'm sure there must have been someone else, maybe several others, of whom I'm not aware, but Mrs. Rutter is still a living legend at Texas A&M today.
And when you think how long her husband has been dead, and the reverence that she still held him today is remarkable.
And I always thought of
Ms.
Rudder as being someone like Lady Bird Johnson.
And I don't know Lady Bird Johnson, but I think that Ms.
Rudder and Lady Bird Johnson at least appear to have been those who could smooth the ruffled feathers that might have been created by their spouses.
And I've never heard anyone speak unkindly about the other.
And I think they were great assets for their husbands.
I think that Mrs. Rutter has seen much more prominent now than she did while he was president.
Well, I felt she was then, too.
I just thought that, to me, Mrs. Rutter is someone
who men like and women like.
There's no jealousy.
She's not pretentious.
She's very proud of her children and her children like all other children.
They didn't grow up without some bumps in some of their roads.
She didn't try to hide it.
She was proud to have the children.
So I think she was just
a complete asset for Earl Rutherford and for Texas A&M.
Mrs. Williams.
Mrs. Williams, I didn't know her.
And I think that says something about it.
I think that she probably preferred it that way.
She was not doing it in public.
And her appearance in the school, she was much happier being less visible and obviously didn't operate it.
feel any need to compete with the reputation that Mr. Weber had.
But I also had the feeling that he was very strong.
Alright, let's jump back then to Jarvis.
It's now the summer of 1980 and you and I know now that Jarvis would be terminated by the board.
Were you aware of any of that coming?
I was not surprised.
As I told you earlier, when Frank Hewitt was Dean of Liberal Arts and Education, I ranked him certainly as one of the top administrators, university administrators I'd ever known, and maybe the tops.
I thought he, I viewed him very differently after he became Chancellor.
Since I have a theory for everything, my theory about this is that I think there were board members who were committed to weakening the role of the president of Texas A&M.
I think that they believed that that person had just had too much power and had used it and had not been as sensitive to the role of the board as they would like for that person to have been.
And I have imagined that it was a possibility, not a likelihood, that they told Frank Hewitt that they wanted to develop a strong assistant officer, and the chancellor being a strong chancellor.
If that happened, and everything that Frank Hewitt did made perfect sense, then clearly the authority of the president of Texas A&M diminished.
Do you remember some particular differences, disagreements between Ebert and Jarvis?
I think the main differences were over money.
There was a lot of relatively flexible money available within the university, and I think Jarvis was predisposed toward making decisions.
about the allocation of those funds within the President's office and with a couple of very close advisors.
And since George's background was in agriculture, I think it was viewed at least that maybe agriculture was getting more than its fair share.
And from some board members' point of view, it's my belief.
that they believe engineering was not getting the attention they deserve.
Are you aware of any particular disagreements you've had with any of the deans over our patients?
No, I'm not.
And with Mack?
Mack was very closely involved with Jarvis in the allocation of funds.
He and, as far as I'm aware, the two of them were fairly... And Howard Vestal.
And Howard Vestal were, okay.
Now, let's talk about some of those people.
Describe Professor Vestal and what his task was and his talents.
Howard was a retired Air Force officer.
a nice man, jovial, and at the same time, he'd been a colonel, and would be treated like a colonel, and thought like a colonel, and acted like a colonel.
With all those things, he was still a really nice person, so a nice combination of things.
Howard always impressed me as someone that I would trust.
But I'm convinced that there's got to be a school somewhere for our vice presidents for finance and our business.
And the number one thing that they learn and the thing you have to prove that you've learned before you graduate is that you never tell anyone all there is to know about where the money is.

So vice presidents of business seem to like to have, you know, some discretion about where the money is and be able to come up with some funds that will literally let a president do what the president really would like to do.
That makes the vice president of business a very, very important person.
But, you know, again, we had a series of events because Earl Rudder obviously developed a very
image and often his land commissioner and his views had a lot of integrity.
And then he brought Clark Diebel, who I understand was told, you know, I want you to let me do what I want to do, but I'm going to keep me out of Huntsville too.
And I think Clark was again one of those that had a lot of integrity.
And so I think we were blessed with a series of people in the financial office during that period of time.
that helped A&M develop a very good reputation in Brazos County and in Austin.
And I think Howard continued that.
Who was the Chief Financial Officer?
After Tom Cherry.
During Williams' administration?
Yeah, that's right.
I think it probably changed with him and then with George.
He was the number two man for a time.
Right.
Then the chief student officer during those years.
Well, during those years, John Coates.
John came from East Texas, now Texas A&M University at Congress.
John was a really good selection.
One of my better judgments, I was asked to apply for that job and chose not to.
They chose the right person.
John was a very good choice.
I remember the part of the, one of the luncheons, one of the luncheons, I was there over on the Rudder Tower.
And I was nicely impressed with Cole.
That's when I thought, gee, surely we can do better than somebody from Texas.
What made him such a good student officer?
I think the fact that he's so outgoing with students and everyone else.
He was certainly not anywhere close to being typical at A&M.
I'm always kind of surprised that John has said, ever since I've known him, he's a kisser and a hugger to me.
And so he was a lot more hands-on in a socially acceptable way with a lot of people.
And again, I think John was creative in a lot of the programs he brought to student services.
So to me he made a, what I would guess would be a pretty big adjustment from a Commonwealth student to A&M.
But I'm going to get into a student life program that I can be very proud of.
Can you think of any special decisions or transitions that coupled this?
Well,
I'm not sure how it evolved, but we got away from the Dean of Men and Dean of Women approach, and I think that was probably the national trend.
But we had a fairly tumultuous period for a short period of time.
My brother, Toby Shriver, he changed the name, I think, three times in two years.
We hired her under one name.
She came here with another name, and then she took a third name, and she went back to Shriver.
as needing women.
I think John made the right decision on what to do about some personnel matters.
I think there were some things that happened that might not have been John's first choice, but he handled them very well.
There had been a disagreement among board members and some of the university administrators about additional on-campus housing.
For a while, the decision appeared to be that we were not going to do it anymore.
We'd let the community take care of that, and we realized the community wasn't taking care of that.
So then we built several more dorms.
So I think the student life program at A&M has done very well.
Thanks to a lot of people, I think the student services through the MSC have been very good.
And I said, John, you seem to be at the lead
go with the flow, make sure they went in the right direction.
All right, now I'm about to go off into areas that I know almost nothing about.
I learned the night we arrived in El Paso to begin our new task out there that Jarvis had been terminated here.
How did your assignment change after Jarvis was no longer president, or did it change?
Not really.
It was obvious that Frank Hubert had won in the eyes of the board.
And that's when Chuck Sampson came in to serve as interim president.
Chuck's style was very different from Jarvis's.
How so?
Well, as I said, Jarvis had more of what I think was the ag-slash-political approach.
He was very interested and concerned in the sense that things that were happening could be happening and might happen in Austin.
Chuck, as a former department head in engineering,
I think had the engineering approach and he was much more methodical and much more analytical.
I think Chuck probably wanted a lot more information than he was likely to get before he would make the decision.
And constantly I think some of the decisions were not made.
as quickly as they might have been.
Did he bring any staff with him?
Not that I can remember.
He took often three briefcases and stuff with him home each night.
I don't think you can find a better person than Chuck Simms.
As far as y'all were aware here,
Was he hoping he would be considered for the task permanently?
I certainly had that feeling.
That would have been my guess.
And when did you all learn that he wasn't going to?
I think there were a couple presentations to board members that he made that were
As far as you know, who were the board members calling in?
Who were the most impressionable, the most influential board members?
I guess...
I don't think Peter Bell was in honor, but he was certainly not more influential when he was honored.
Ross Wiseman was always a dominant member of the board.
I don't know if there was a board member calling the shots then.
I don't know who it was.
I don't know.
Bumbright, I guess, would be number one.
When I chat with... McKenzie.
Bill McKenzie.
I bet so.
See, what I'm hoping to build up to is to know what questions to ask them.
Okay, then when did y'all become aware that the president of North Texas State might be the new president here?
Very late.
Bunbright, as I remember, had made an announcement that we would have a new president named by a certain point in time.
And the time was getting very close.
And then I think most of us were surprised when Frank Bannon offered the job and had accepted it.
And I think that there was some who believed that the announced date of the driving force
in the selection process.
When did Frank Menninger first, when did y'all first see him, meet with him?
I guess right after he became the board.
So there was no first presentation?
Not that I know of.
Describe his leadership style.
Exciting.
Frank is one of the most interesting people I've ever known in my life.
He can be so presidential at times, it's just awe-inspiring.
All of a sudden he's changing his mind quickly.
I served as interim vice president for Aging Affairs for a period of time and I felt I needed to be very flexible because there would be some times that Frank might be expected to be somewhere else.
His plans would change and so he had to have plan B ready all the time.
But again, he's bright, and he's articulate, and he's very, very charming.
Now the, he, did Mack, Mack remain?
Yes.
And retired?
And so that Frank made no particular personnel changes in the leadership team?
Not in the leadership team, except as I said, I became the vice president.
He brought in Sharon Riley, who proved, I think, to do a very good job.
And he brought Eddie Joe back from North Texas.
to be the chief financial officer.
Then Gordon Eaton, you were interim and then Gordon Eaton?
Correct.
Talk about Gordon and his style.
Gordon Eaton was a very bright, charming, thoughtful, sensitive man.
He was admired, I think, by almost all the faculty.
Again, never trying to impress them with his background, but was impressive with his background.
One of the easiest people to talk to that I've ever met.
One of the things that
that I liked about his statement.
I never felt that he suggested there might be another way he might want to consider something before he made the decision.
And as I said earlier, he had to be very careful because if he made the suggestion, he might not well do it.
It didn't turn out what he felt.
He's a very confident person in himself.

can deal with anyone faculty legislators like experience with the u.s geological survey must have served him well i think one of the most thoughtful men i've ever met any key decisions during this one of the
Gordon wasn't, you know, in that role very long.
A couple years, three years maybe.
And then, then do you go to Iowa State with him?
With him.
With him, that's right.
And that's when?
In, uh, 86?
Okay.
Alright, now, so then let's look back.
Uh, who were some special students that you may have
worked with, advised, or known, that you now hold warmly in your heart?
One person who got me on the course was Ken Capeley.
Ken was one of those obvious student leaders when he was here.
He was involved with the Liberal Arts Student Council.

Two of the things that I felt good about the Liberal Arts Student Council, primarily, I guess, they helped me do what I'd like to get done, and that is convert from the three-point grading system to the four-point grading system.
Because we were one of the very few institutions in the country in the three-point.
And the Liberal Arts Student Council was the one that advanced the idea of going to the four-point system.
And the other was the QDROP policy.
And I remember
You know, working with Kent, I was the advisor for the student council, and working with him to try to get the QDROP accepted, and it was rejected.
And then when Kent came back on the staff with Jack Williams, it went through verbatim.
And I remember telling Kent, when he was a student, you know, I said, Kent, you don't win everything.
I said, this is bad and nasty.
I said, sometimes someone plows the soil, and someone plants a seed, and someone fertilizes it, and somebody waters it, and someone else may gather the fruit.
But when it did pass, I pulled it out and gave it to Kent to remind him that he had been a major player in preparing the ground.
Roger Miller, who was a journalism major, who I thought was very talented,
I had hoped would also run the politics.
Chet Edwards was another one.
They were all here at the same time.
Those were probably the three that came along together that I thought a lot about.
One that is different, but it's kind of interesting how people, you can influence someone.
This one I didn't, but anyway.
I have a grandson who played at Westlake this year, as you know.
And so his father and mother hosted the Westlake football team for Thursday night meals for 13 weeks.
And so it came up that Myna Brees, Myna Adkins when she was here, is the mother of Drew Brees who was the quarterback at Purdue.
And so Gary and Myna were
in school at the same time here.
And so it came up in the conversation that I was Gary's father-in-law.
So Gary made a point that we'd meet at one of the Westlake football games.
And so she reminded me that I had given her an award as a liberal arts student.
And she was one of the first Diamond Darlings.
And her brother is Marty Akins.
And her father was a high school coach for a long time.

And so I was talking to her about Drew, you know, not coming to A&M, and it was obvious she was not very happy because Drew had been told he'd be invited for a visit to A&M and never had the invitation offered.
And so, anyway, he's done fairly well at Purdue this year.
Your proudest moments as you look back?
I think the proudest moment was not a moment in time, but I would like to think that I was viewed as someone who helped get things done.
I think degree-wise, program-wise, facility-wise, being the chairman of the master planning committee

One of the things that I'm very proud of is that when I first got involved in the master planning committee, I had a list of all the buildings that were going to be torn down, and it was almost everything.
And I'd like to think that I was one of them who said, you know, the diversity of that architecture on the campus is an asset.
And so there are a lot of buildings still standing that were renovated and all that, and we're scheduled to be torn down.
The Ag building over by the library, the pavilion was going to be torn down.
Most of the old quad buildings were scheduled to be torn down.
And I just thought that would have been tragic.
And so anyway, you look around the campus and say, well, we had some influence on some of those things.
So it's really, someone asked me, you know, what it's like to be a university administrator.
And I tried to give an honest answer.
And when I picked someone up, I said, well, the way you described it, why would anyone want to be one?
And I said, well, I didn't really intend to do that.
But I said, you know, to me, if you think you know what a good university is about,
you're much more likely to influence the direction of the university as an administrator than you are as a faculty member.
And that's the satisfaction.
To believe that A&M or Iowa State are better institutions today and that you helped make them.
